lisa-design:
- BLOCKERS (API prompt not yet shipped; probed live against the local stack with an admin token):
  404 GET /oscal/system-security-plans/:id/shared-responsibility
  404 GET /oscal/ssp-export-offerings/by-control/:controlId
  404 {GET,POST,PUT,DELETE} .../statements/:stmtId/by-components/:bcId/inherited
  404 {GET,POST,PUT,DELETE} .../statements/:stmtId/by-components/:bcId/satisfied
  404 DELETE .../implemented-requirements/:reqId/by-components/:bcId
  no meta.created on POST .../subscribe
  Already live (verified 400 = route exists): statement-level .../export{,/provided,/responsibilities},
  and .../export-offerings/:offeringId/allowed-downstreams.
  Per the prompt these are implemented against the contract and unit-tested with mocked axios;
  they are NOT worked around in the UI. Every consumer degrades to an empty state rather than
  crashing (verified in-browser: the Controls panel renders its empty states under a 404).
- The allow-list path is /system-security-plans/:id/export-offerings/:offeringId/allowed-downstreams
  (what the API actually exposes), not the /ssp-export-offerings/:id/... form the prompt sketched.
- Statement presence is the single switch for authoring. ByComponentEditForm renders the full
  editors when `statement` is passed and a read-only view when it isn't; the requirement-level
  path therefore cannot create or edit export/inherited/satisfied by construction, not by a flag.
- The by-component PUT now strips inherited and satisfied as well as export. All three subtrees
  have dedicated endpoints and their own editors; sending them here would race those writes.
- Inherited/Satisfied are separate components rather than one generic editor: their create-time
  anchors differ (providedUuid is free-text from the upstream export; responsibilityUuid must be
  picked from what the statement actually inherits, or the API 400s), and both are immutable
  after create, so the edit forms are genuinely different shapes.
- The satisfied picker's options come from the shared-responsibility rollup's inherits[], filtered
  to this statement. That required adding `responsibilities` to SharedResponsibilityInherited.
- A 409 on deleting an inherited entry means a subscription owns it. It is caught and toasted as
  "unsubscribe from the offering", and the row survives. The UI never touches the leverage link.
- useOfferableCapabilities now returns capabilities (statement-anchored, offerable) and
  legacyCapabilities (requirement-anchored, listed disabled). The composite de-dupe key is
  unchanged. ExportOfferingItemsDialog also refuses a legacy tuple client-side even if the
  disabled option were bypassed, and renders the API's 400 inline next to the picker.
- ExportOfferingsPanel is the extraction: both the SSP-editor route and the new system:export-offerings
  tab render it. It fetches through execute() against COMPUTED urls, which is also the <KeepAlive>
  stale-fetch fix (useDataApi resolves toValue(url) once). Same fix applied to
  SystemSecurityPlanInheritedCapabilitiesView. Their specs now assert the URL per execute() call.
- SharedResponsibilityBlocks is the consolidation of the two divergent StatementByComponent
  copies' four export blocks. The Badge-based (control-implementations) styling won.
- Cross-linking a LeveragedAuthorization to the offering that created it is NOT possible: the
  leveraged-controls projection carries no leveragedAuthUuid, so there is no id to join on. Added a
  navigational link to Inherited Capabilities instead, and noted the missing field.
- SubscribeOfferingWizard was parameterized (scopedItemIds/preselectedItemIds), not forked, and now
  emits {links, meta} so the Controls view can expand+highlight the requirements meta.created names.
  Rows with created:false are deliberately not announced.
